Figures and Tables

STOP

Ask yourself these questions:

  1. What kind of data are you trying to display? Nominal, ordinal, or continuous? 1a. If you are displaying nominal/ordinal, is it frequency, proportion, or percentage?

  2. What information are you interested in showing and does it all need to be shown?

  3. Would you benefit from breaking it down into multiple figures?

What should graphs do?

  • Show data
  • Make the reader think about the data being presented (not the aesthetic choices of the graph)
  • Avoid distorting the data
  • Present the maximum amount of information with the minimum amount of detail (avoid “chartjunk” [Tufte, 2001])
  • Make large amounts of data concise and coherent
  • Facilitate comparisons between data

Have in graphs

  • Clearly outlined figure titles (main and axis labels)
  • Appropriate scales (scales should be just as large as it takes to adequately fit the data, no larger - if your values end at 50, do not have a figure that goes up to 100)
  • If you have a regresson line, have the equation and the r value in the figure

Avoid in graphs

  • Do not use 3D to plot 2D data

  • Do not use unnecessary patterns, particularly when they are similar to each other or when distracting from the data

  • Do not have crazy colors, but make sure that they are distinct from each other - keep in mind that figures may be published in black and white
    • When published in color, keep in mind potential colorblindedness

  • Do not magnify or reduce the scale more than is necessary to display all of the information, particularly when you are changing the scale to enhance or reduce certain comparisons

Bar Charts

  • Best for categorical (nominal/ordinal) data or discrete continuous data (ex: population size, settlement number, burial number, etc.)
  • Allows you to examine relative counts/comparisons of data between categories or groups
  • Requires a vector or matrix
Eurovision <- read.csv("EurovisionWinners.csv")
table(Eurovision$Language)

barplot(table(Eurovision$Language), main = "Language of Winning Song of Eurovision", xlab = "Language", ylab = "Frequency of Occurrence", col = "midnightblue")


#"ylim = " Manually adjusts the scale of the y-axis; "xlim =" would adjust the x-axis scale
barplot(table(Eurovision$Country), main = "Country of Winning Song of Eurovision", xlab = "Country", ylab = "Frequency of Occurrence", col = "midnightblue", ylim= c(0,40))

Stacked Bar Charts

library(RColorBrewer)

CollectionA <- c(56,112,34,5,3,1)
CollectionB <- c(28,97,47,6,4,3)
CollectionC <- c(14,62,8,63,7,45)
Tab <- cbind(CollectionA, CollectionB, CollectionC)
Tab <- as.matrix(Tab)

rownames(Tab) <- c("African American","European American", "Hispanic American", "Asian American", "Native American", "Pacific Islander American")

#"legend.text = TRUE" adds a legend
#"args.legend = " passes all of the arguments that you would put in a legend() function to an argumented nested within the barplot() function
barplot(Tab, legend.text = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 225), col = palette("Dark2"),main = "Demographic Composition of Collections", xlab = "Collection", ylab = "Number of Individuals", args.legend = list(x="right", bty='n', cex = 0.3, inset=c(-0.25,0)))

Grouped Bar Charts

#Adding "beside = TRUE" puts each bar next to each other, rather than on top
barplot(Tab, beside = TRUE, legend.text = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 225), col = palette("Dark2"),main = "Demographic Composition of Collections", xlab = "Collection", ylab = "Number of Individuals", args.legend = list(x="right", bty='n', cex = 0.3, inset=c(-0.25,0)))

Histogram

  • Best for continuous data
  • “Bins” the data; “bins” are the number of classes/bars created for the histogram

  • In addition to the bars, particularly helpful to add a line

  • You can have a frequency histogram (the default)

    • Areas of the bars add up to the number of observations
library(archdata)
data("BACups")

hist(BACups$ND, ylim = c(0,25), main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Diameter", xlab = "Bronze Age Cups Measurement (in cm)", ylab = "Frequency")


#"breaks = " indicates how many bins/bars you want to have in your histogram
hist(BACups$ND, breaks = 10, ylim = c(0,25), main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Diameter", xlab = "Bronze Age Cups Measurement (in cm)", ylab = "Frequency")

#To add density plot line; "lwd = " is the thickness of the plotted line
lines(x = density(BACups$ND), col = "red", lwd = 2)

  • A density histogram
    • Areas of the bars add up to one
library(archdata)
data("BACups")

#"freq = FALSE" turns it into a density histogram
hist(BACups$ND, breaks = 10, freq= FALSE, ylim = c(0,.1), main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Diameter", xlab = "Bronze Age Cups Measurement (in cm)", ylab = "Density")
lines(x = density(BACups$ND), col = "red", lwd = 2)

  • A percentage histogram
    • Areas of the bars add up to 100
library(archdata)
data("BACups")

#"scale = "percent"" turns it into a percentage histogram
hist(BACups$ND, breaks = 10, scale = "percent", ylim = c(0,20), main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Diameter", xlab = "Bronze Age Cups Measurement (in cm)", ylab = "Percentage")
lines(x = density(BACups$ND), col = "red", lwd = 2)

  • An approximation of the distribution using a smooth curve
  • The area under the curve is equal to one

Line Plot

  • A line plot is use for tracking change over a variable (particularly time)
  • It is essentially a scatterplot, but with one data point per variable and connected by a line
Euro2 <- read.csv("Eurovision2.csv")

#Adding the "type = "l"" argument changes a scatterplot to a line plot
plot(Euro2$Number.of.Countries.Participating, type = "l", ylab = "Number of Countries", xlab = "Year")


#To put values on axis (use "xaxt="n"" to remove default x-axis values)
plot(Euro2$Number.of.Countries.Participating, type = "l", main = "Number of Countries Participating in Eurovision", ylab = "Number of Countries", xlab = "Year",xaxt="n")

#This tell R to change all values (1:64) on the x-axis (1) to the labels found in your data frame (labels = Euro2$Year)
axis(1,at=1:64,labels = Euro2$Year)


#To label points using values
#text(Euro2$Number.of.Countries.Participating, labels = Euro2$Year, cex=.8, col="black")

#To add multiple lines

X <- seq(1,32,0.5)

plot(Euro2$Number.of.Countries.Participating, type = "l", main = "Number of Countries Participating in Eurovision", ylab = "Number of Countries", xlab = "Year", ylim = c(0,45), xaxt="n")
lines(Euro2$Number.of.Countries.Debuting, col = "red")
lines(X, col = "blue")

#Or

#Superimposes plots on top of each other
par(new=TRUE)

plot(Euro2$Number.of.Countries.Debuting, type = "l", main = "Number of Countries Participating in Eurovision", ylab = "Number of Countries", xlab = "Year",ylim = c(0,45), xaxt="n", col = "red")
axis(1,at=1:64,labels = Euro2$Year)

Scatterplot

  • Plots data points to exhibit the relationship between two variables
#"pch = " indicates the shape of the data point
plot(BACups$NH, BACups$ND, main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Height compared to Neck Diameter", xlab = "Measurement of Neck Height (in cm)", ylab = "Measurement of Neck Diameter (in cm)", pch = 16)


plot(BACups$ND ~ BACups$NH, main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Height compared to Neck Diameter", xlab = "Measurement of Neck Height (in cm)", ylab = "Measurement of Neck Diameter (in cm)", pch = 16)


#If you have multiple instances of overlapping points (very common, for instance, when plotting estimated age versus chronological age), then you may use the jitter() function in R to add a slight value to each of those data points so that it shifts slightly around each other and you can see all of the points
plot(jitter(BACups$ND) ~ jitter(BACups$NH), main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Height compared to Neck Diameter", xlab = "Measurement of Neck Height (in cm)", ylab = "Measurement of Neck Diameter (in cm)", pch = 16)


#To create a unique character for the different groups in your plot, create a vector that contains the pch characters you want to use and then insert that vector into the "pch = " argument (or the same for colors)
colors <- c("#1B9E77", "#D95f02")
colors <- colors[as.numeric(BACups$Phase)]

pch <- c(16,17)
pch <- pch[as.numeric(BACups$Phase)]

BACupsPlot<- plot(jitter(BACups$ND) ~ jitter(BACups$NH), main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Height compared to Neck Diameter", xlab = "Measurement of Neck Height (in cm)", ylab = "Measurement of Neck Diameter (in cm)", pch = pch, col = colors)

legend("topright",legend=c("Protoapennine","Subapennine"),pch=pch,col = colors,cex=0.75)


library(car)
scatterplot(BACups$ND ~ BACups$NH|BACups$Phase)

It may often be a good idea to add a line of best fit (regression line) to help illustrate a relationship, especially when the relationship is not super clear

plot(BACups$NH, BACups$ND, main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Height compared to Neck Diameter", xlab = "Measurement of Neck Height (in cm)", ylab = "Measurement of Neck Diameter (in cm)")

#This function adds a regression line
#lm() is essentially creating a linear model where you are predicting ND from NH
abline(lm(BACups$ND~BACups$NH), col = "red")

You may find that a regression line is not the best fit for your data - either your data are not linearly related or you are interested in depicting more specific relationships

Loess line: Locally weighted scatterplot smoothing

plot(BACups$NH, BACups$ND, main = "Bronze Age Cups Neck Height compared to Neck Diameter", xlab = "Measurement of Neck Height (in cm)", ylab = "Measurement of Neck Diameter (in cm)")

#This function creates a loess line where NH predicts ND
BA<-loess(BACups$ND ~ BACups$NH, span = 1, BACups)

#Creates a line of the predicted loess line
lines(predict(BA))

Plotting each pair of variables in a data frame

plot(BACups[1:5], main = "All Pairwise Comparisons of Bronze Age Cups")

library(scatterplot3d)

#Plots in three dimensions
scatterplot3d(BACups[1:3], main = "3D Plot of Diameter Measurements of Bronze Age Cups", ylab = "Neck Diameter", xlab = "Rim Diameter", zlab = "Stem Diameter")

scatterplot3d(BACups[1:3], main = "3D Plot of Diameter Measurements of Bronze Age Cups", ylab = "Neck Diameter", xlab = "Rim Diameter", zlab = "Stem Diameter", type = "h", pch=16)


#color = "steelblue" changed the color of the points and lines (if lines are included in the scatterplot)
S3D <- scatterplot3d(BACups[1:3],main = "3D Plot of Diameter Measurements of Bronze Age Cups", ylab = "Neck Diameter", xlab = "Rim Diameter", zlab = "Stem Diameter", type = "h", pch=16, color = "steelblue")

#Adds labels to the data points; "labels =" indicates which columns hold the label names; "cex = " indicates the size of the label font 
text(S3D$xyz.convert(BACups[1:3]),main = "3D Plot of Diameter Measurements of Bronze Age Cups", ylab = "Neck Diameter", xlab = "Rim Diameter", zlab = "Stem Diameter", labels = BACups$Phase, cex= 0.5)

Q-Q Plot

  • Quantile-Quantile plots (Q-Q Plots) are used to examine a data set for normality
    • It standardizes your data so that it can be compared to an ideal normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1
    • A perfect normal distirbution would have all data points fall neatly on the plotted line
library(ggpubr)

#A single variable
ggqqplot(BACups$ND)


#A Q-Q Plot for a single variable for both levels of a categorical group
by(BACups$ND, BACups$Phase, ggqqplot)

BACups$Phase: Protoapennine


------------------------------------------------------------ 
BACups$Phase: Subapennine

Boxplot

  • Useful for examining a quick snapshot of your data
    • Can provide some indication of variability, normality, homogeneity between groups if multiple groups are in the same boxplot, idneitfication of outliers
    • The box represents the interquartile range (IQR); the line in the box represents the median; the “whiskers” represent the IQR*1.5 added and subtracted to Q3 and Q1, respectively; and any circles beyond these whiskers represent outliers
#A single variable
boxplot(BACups$ND)


#A single variable but separated by a particular factor/categorical value
boxplot(BACups$ND~BACups$Phase)


#Multiple variables in the same plot
boxplot(BACups[2:4])

Do not use pie charts

  • Studies have shown that the brain cannot efficiently interpret the proportions of different pie slices, resulting in a lack of ability to understand the data

Data <- c(64,79,88,56,100)

pie(Data, col = palette("Dark2"))


barplot(Data, col = palette("Dark2"))

What to have in tables

  • Always include units of measurement in your tables (Can be summed in column/row headers or in description) - avoid using units of measurement in each individual cell as it creates clutter (remember, minimal amount of detail as possible)
  • Include sample size for each group/variable
  • Include standard error, range, or 95% confidence interval as much as possible
  • Include precise p-values (no p < 0.05)
  • If you have abbreviations, be sure to explain them in footnotes or table description
  • Minimize the amount of data needed to be presented in a table
    • While you may want to show everything, ensure that you are showing only what needs to be shown, in a clear and concise way
    • Avoid putting too many variables in a single table
  • Insert a dash in a cell where data was not able to be obtained, leave blank if the cell is not meant to have data either way
  • Do not add too much white space in each cell
    • In general, this will be enough white on either side of the entry as what is required by the column headings and then about the same amount of white space both above and below the numbers are equal to the size of the numbers
  • Assist in differentiating one line from another (either through shading or line breaks)
    • Many journals have their own formatting systems
  • Use visual cues to assst the reader with the flow of information

Frequency Distribution

A frequency distribution is a table that displays the count of observations

Tables and Figures

  • Should be able to be understood without referencing the text
  • Should not be simply a repetition of the text
    • While the text may reference the table or figure, these should include more contextual information
